This was an interesting, engaging, unique, well-designed, and enjoyable activity and one which I would love to partake in again. I found this article particularly interesting which made the activity even more enjoyable. Regarding the actual utility/helpfulness of the images shown previously, I really did not find them very useful, even the ones that I chose were mediocre at best. Perhaps images illustrating the recycling process (e.g. a diagram or schematic demonstrating a general sketch/outline of the recycling) would be more useful and enhance the interest of readers. Additionally, images/diagrams/schematics demonstrating the locations of the various metals recycled as detailed in the article would be very helpful (e.g. I didn't choose the motherboard/CPU images, however, I think it would be really useful and helpful to include an iteration of the motherboard/CPU image that uses an actual Apple device instead of a non-Apple device that contains labels for each component as detailed in the article e.g. images with the motherboard and  CPU that include labels for the various recycled components e.g label the camera component with gold and copper etc.) Another helpful image would be one of the Liam prototype, if available, or or something similar to the Liam prototype so that the reader can develop a better, more tangible, palpable, and clearer idea of this really cool machine. Anyway, as you can tell, I really enjoyed this activity, hence, the massive block of text written. Great activity, hope more activities like this one are offered.
